What I loved about cartelshit is they put emphasis on the filmmaking, by embracing the stylized neo-western aesthetic. All these scenes were designed around visual storytelling and slowburn pacing, building tension and delaying payoffs, the importance of small details against wide scenery, characters doing physical acts and interacting in larger environments, with the slowburn pacing or more abstract storytelling concepts pushed to almost absurd degrees at times. Like ants eating ice cream or Mike digging a hole for a 10 minutes sequence.

All of these characters are nonsense men of few words, by contrast words and bullshit are Jimmy's main weapon.

Except for the intros or occasional montages, most Jimmy scenes were dialogues-driven and flatly shot in closeups/in spatially limited environments like offices.

For me BCS was always at its best when it was focused on some weird visual and moody storytelling, just like BrBa, stuff like the pink teddy bear in the pool, Mexicans crawling in the desert, etc up to Howard's car on the beach or the tequila's cork on the pavement during the fed raid. What does that have to do with anything? How did we get there? How can such a trivial detail yet feel so ominous? And cartelshit had a lot more naturally fitting emphasis on this type of stuff.

>>180210446
Holy goddamn, a near masterpiece, it's the kind of film that by itself shows the director is a master. Caught me totally off-guard with the ridiculously ambitious storytelling, the wild emotions, the mythological characterizations, the frenetic bravado pace. It's SPRAWLING. It keeps surprising by weaving a completely coherent magical-realist-decades-long depiction of a community through its many near extinctions and ever-evolving dynamics. And after great success, it abandons the broad view and centers on an unlikely and electric love story, while making the viewer root for- suddenly- our literal heroes. It reminded of at times of Amarcord, also Freaks, also They Live By Night, also O Thiasos, also Apocalypse Now. And it's surely in that company of such spectacular cinema, pretty much impossible to leave anyone who watches it not thrilled. And what music to guide all these affairs! My favorite and best of 2023, and straight to the top of 1997 and near the top of the 90s. I'll be definitely checking out Jakubisko's other works ahead. Of the films I've watched because of heavy shilling here, it's second only to The Cremator.

Very much liked La La Land too, if some leagues below An Ambitious Report. A melancholical musical romance, I specially liked Chazelle's rhythms and the end section exploring the life that was not. The best thing of the film is the Hurwitz's score, its dance of vitality and longing. To watch soon the much infamous Babylon, but the three I've seen from him all were of my liking.

All in all, a great night.

That's because Scott ties too much of his ego into the film, like "I'm the director and I'm making MY ART" which is why Prometheus and Covenant sucked because he wanted to shoe-horn in ideas about God, religion, the origin of man and creation, which completely tanked those films that are supposed to be about the unknown horrors of space.
Cameron on the other hand is a self-described populist film-maker he wants to make films that appeal to as many people as possible, so while he also has a message he wants to push, his intention is to make the film resonate with people so that message reaches them, but beyond that he is just making films about the things that interest him, forests, oceans, cool tech, exploration, giant blue chicks, and as he says in an interview talking about how the studio was complaining about the length of the flying scene in the first Avatar his reasoning was "If I want to see it, then chances are a lot of other people will want to see it as well."
